&lt;p class="p1"&gt;The AGGREGATION Project is situated within work on applying computational methods to endangered language documentation. In particular, we are interested in automatically developing computational grammars for languages on the basis of two kinds of rich linguistic resources: collections of data annotated with morpheme-by-morpheme glosses and translations for the language, on the one hand, and a cross-linguistic grammar customization system (called the LinGO Grammar Matrix), on the other. The Grammar Matrix stores analyses for different kinds of grammatical phenomena that vary across languages (e.g., how a language expresses negation or forms questions). It takes in a grammar specification and outputs a working, machine-readable grammar that meets that specification. These grammars can take sentences written in the languages they go with and output grammatical structures including representations of the sentence meaning. Our goal in this project is to create software that can output the grammar specifications on the basis of annotated data collections produced by documentary linguists so that a grammar can automatically be generated.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;The AGGREGATION Project (Phase II) has made the following advances:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;We extended the Grammar Matrix to include analyses for subordinate clauses, &lt;em&gt;wh&lt;/em&gt; questions (&lt;em&gt;who&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;what&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;where&lt;/em&gt;), and other phenomena.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;We extended the AGGREGATION inference system to integrate lexical and morphological inference with syntactic inference, increased the richness of morphological rules by integrating syntactic features and extended the syntactic phenomena that can be handled.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;We built an integrated, end-to-end pipeline that starts with data collections from field linguists and produces working grammars.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;We evaluated the system with datasets from 14 languages from all around the world: Abui, Arapaho, Chintang, Hiaki, Hixkaryana, Lezgi, Matsigenka, Meithei, Nuuchahnulth, South Efate, Titan, Tsova-Tush, Wakhi and Wambaya.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;We built visualization software to help linguists who provide datasets explore the patterns that our inference system extracts.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;We held a workshop to train field linguists to use the software and elicit their feedback on how to improve it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p class="p1"&gt;These systems have both immediate and long term impacts on linguistic research and speaker communities. For linguistic research, automatically derived computational grammars can help documentary linguists explore their data, discover counterexamples to proposed generalizations, and find further items of interest not already handled by their analyses. The implemented grammars also provide starting points for creating robust language resources which can in turn support language technology. We anticipate that our work will lead to more and better language documentation which in turn will support language revitalization efforts by communities around the world. Language revitalization has additional benefits in strengthening communities. Furthermore, language technology for endangered languages can enhance the prestige of those languages and thus their long-term maintenance.&lt;/p&gt;

